Background

A Portguese bank is interested in identifying factors that affect client responses to new term deposit offerings in order to develop targeted marketing campaigns. The bank has collected results from seventeen past marketing campaigns, which include a wide variety of information.

The goal of this analysis is two-fold: 1) to better understand which clients are most likely to subscribe to new term deposits, and 2) to understand what marketing approaches are most effective. A key requirement for this analysis is to incorporate information on if a client has credit in default, if a client has a housing loan, and if a client has a personal loan. Both logistic regression and Naive Bayes models are considered to answer the key questions, and commentary is provided model results and next steps.

Data Preparation

We begin this analysis by loading several packages and reading in our data frame. This data is comprised of 4,521 rows and 17 columns.

# need to adjust some data types for modeling
# before we do this, we want to preserve our original df
bank_clean = bank_df.copy()
# mapping function to convert text no/yes to integer 0/1
convert_to_binary = {'yes':1, 'no':0}

default = bank_clean['default'].map(convert_to_binary)
bank_clean['default'] = default
housing = bank_clean['housing'].map(convert_to_binary)
bank_clean['housing'] = housing
loan = bank_clean['loan'].map(convert_to_binary)
bank_clean['loan'] = loan
response = bank_clean['response'].map(convert_to_binary)
bank_clean['response'] = response

# convert other vars to character vars for now
bank_clean['job'] = bank_clean['job'].astype('category')         
bank_clean['marital'] = bank_clean['marital'].astype('category')   
bank_clean['education'] = bank_clean['education'].astype('category')   
bank_clean['month'] = bank_clean['month'].astype('category')   
bank_clean['contact'] = bank_clean['contact'].astype('category')

In [879]:
def corr_chart(df_corr):
    corr=df_corr.corr()
    #screen top half to get a triangle
    top = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
    top[np.triu_indices_from(top)] = True
    fig=plt.figure()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,15))
    sns.heatmap(corr, mask=top, cmap='coolwarm', 
        center = 0, square=True, 
        linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={'shrink':.5}, 
        annot = True, annot_kws={'size': 9}, fmt = '.2f')           
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right') # rotate variable labels on columns (x axis), add adjustment so text appears right by axis ticks
    plt.yticks(rotation=0) # use horizontal variable labels on rows (y axis)
    plt.title('Correlation Heat Map')   

corr_chart(bank_clean)

<Figure size 432x288 with 0 Axes>

While the correlation matrix is a bit cumbersome with all variables, it is an easy way to analyze patterns. From the correlation matrix, we can see that most variables do not seem to be related with one another or the response variable. Some trends that do stand out are:

  • There is a strong negative correlation with an unknown outcome on a previous campaign and the number of days have passed from contact.
  • There is a moderately strong negative correlation between unknown outcome on a previous campaign and the number of contacts performed. That is, as contacts goes up, then unknown outcome goes down (which makes intuitive sense).
  • Number of contacts and number of days passed from a previous campaign have a moderately strong positive relationship.
  • The management job type has a moderate negative correlation with education, which seems counter-intuitive (but the definition of management is unknown).
  • The job variables all have a slight negative correlation with one another.

We are now ready to move onto the model building section.

Model Building

In this section, two different models are generated using logistic regression and Naive Bayes. In both cases, models are built using a subset of variables and fit on a training set that was created using a 70/30 split. Three-fold cross validation is used on the training set to build a model. AUC is the primary metric for model evaluation, although many other metrics are considered as well.

Logistic Regression

A logistic model is fit using only the default, housing, and personal loan variables. In this case, a class weight is specified because of the imbalance in classes. It is also worth noting that because of the class imbalance, accuracy is not a metric that is used for model evaluation. Rather, other metrics from the confusion matrix are used.

In [886]:
# we select a subset of vars for model building
bank_sub = bank_clean[['response','default','housing','loan']]
#bank_sub.info()

# define our train & test sets
X, y = bank_sub[['default','housing','loan']], bank_sub['response'] 
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=42)

logreg = LogisticRegression(class_weight = 'balanced', random_state = 42)

log_y_train_pred = cross_val_predict(logreg, X_train, y_train, cv=3)
#cross_val_score(logreg, X_train, y_train, cv=3, scoring="accuracy")

From the training set GOF output below, we can see that this model has an overall AUC of .59, which is not that great. This poor performance can be seen by examining the confusion matrix and precision score. The model precision is very low for the positive responder class, at .17. In other words, when this model claims a client has subscribed to a term deposit, it is only correct in 17% of cases. Morever, it only detects 54% of the term deposit subscribers.

This poor result is due to the variables selected for this model, as from the exploratory data analysis, default and personal loan variables had so few positive cases in them, making them poor predictors.

Naive Bayes Classifier

Before running the Naive Bayes Classifier, some brief context is provided on this modeling approach. A Naive Bayes Classifier is a family of algorithms that is comprised of two different components: an a-priori probability, which is the probability of a subscriber to term deposits, and conditional probabilities for each predictor among respondent classes. Since this model is only considering binary variables as predictors, the conditional probabilities are proportions of that variable.

A Naive Bayes Classifier determines the probability that a client subscribes to term deposits (a-priori) given their attributes (conditional probability), which is called the posterior probability. The class with the highest posterior probability is the outcome of prediction.

In [807]:
nb_model = BernoulliNB(fit_prior = False) # Whether to learn class prior probabilities or not. If false, a uniform prior will be used.
nb_y_train_pred = cross_val_predict(nb_model, X_train, y_train, cv=3)

From the Naive Bayes training set GOF output, we can see that the results are very similar to the logistic regression model above. The AUC is subpar at .59, and the precision is even worse at 16%. However, the recall has improved to 55%. The F1-score will be examined in the next section.

From the test set GOF output above, we can see that both models have similar performance. Both models have an AUC of .61. While this result is also similar to the training set performance, the fact that it is a little bit higher is a sign that we are most likely underfitting.

Both the precision and recall values are very high from one another. These models have very low precision and subpar recall values. The F1-score is a combination of both precision and recall. Since precision and recall are far apart, the F1-score is low for both models.

Another way to analyze the performance of these models is through a precision and threshold curve. Because the classes are more imbalanced, this curve provides precision and recall values at all possible thresholds. This visual is helpful for determing the appropriate cutoff (i.e., precision/recall tradeoff) to use for a given business problem.

In [804]:
precisions_log, recalls_log, thresholds_log = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_y_test_pred)
precisions_nb, recalls_nb, thresholds_nb = precision_recall_curve(y_test, nb_y_test_pred)

def plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(precisions, recalls, thresholds,title):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], "b--", label="Precision")
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], "g-", label="Recall")
    plt.xlabel("Threshold")
    plt.legend(loc="center left")
    plt.ylim([0,1])
    plt.title(title)
    
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize = (15,4))   

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(precisions_log, recalls_log, thresholds_log, 'Logistic Regression Model')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(precisions_nb, recalls_nb, thresholds_nb,'Naive Bayes Model')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Not surprisingly, the precision and recall curves are non intersecting. Recall goes down as the threshold goes up, which is counterintuitive. Thus, a low threshold would be needed for this model, which we only generate mixed results. This overall result is further evidence that both models have poor performance and require being rebuilt using additional predictors.

Bonus: Random Forest Model

Because of the poor performance of both the logistic regression and Naive Bayes model, a random forest model is considered. A random forest model builds multiple decision trees but does so by injecting randomness in the data and variables used to build the trees. Cross validation is not used on the training set due to time constraints. All variables in the data set are considered for the model.

Summary and Conclusions

In summary, this analysis explored client demographic, banking, and marketing campaign characteristics in the hopes of predicting client subscription to a term deposit.

Using the credit in default, housing loan, and personal loan variables, two different models were generated. While these variables were hypothesized to have discriminatory power, the model results were less than ideal. Both models had poor performance on the training and test sets, with low precision and AUC. In contrast, a random forest model was generated and offered improvements to the baseline models. In the future, more time is needed to determine the optimal model for this business problem, with greater balance of business goals and data results. The random forest model helps to show that other variables provide more discriminatory power.

To help improve model results, variable selection should be used when building models. Furthermore, outliers should be examined in greater detail, as several variables contained outliers. Variable transformations could be performed (depending on the model used) to ensure that model results are as accurate as they could be. As always, having greater insight into the business goals will help ensure that the data preparation steps and subsequent model results are appropriate.

In the future, the bank should not use housing or personal loans to target new clients nor analyze their credit in default. In other words, based on this analysis, client banking history (outside of balance) appears to have minimal impact on a client's likelihood to subscribe to new term deposits. Rather, this bank should focus on a client's account balance, data from the most recent campaign, and demographics to determine who to target. This subset could be further divided into more meaningful groups if business/marketing goals were more apparent.

Lastly, in response to the goal of identifying which marketing approaches are most effective, this question still remains hard to answer. If more time allowed, analysis could be performed on some key variables (i.e., duration, balance, age) and better understand the trends in their contact communication type. That being said, the contact communication type variable had a large presence of unknown values. If more direction was provided on how to measure the most effective marketing approach given the data allotted, then this question could be better answered. As it stands, a goal for the upcoming campaign should be to record the contact communication type as well as the response to determine which communication type is correlated with response.
